yarn is an NPM alternative, that is faster and easier to use than npm
the preferred choice in the front end community.

________________________________________________________________________________

*-* command line *-*
________________________________________________________________________________

npm install -g yarn
yarn init
yarn add express --> for 

git init

git add
git commit -m ""
git commit -am "" //or you can do this to add and commit simultaneously
git log //to look for history

mkdir <filename> //create new directory



________________________________________________________________________________

*-* shortcuts *-*
________________________________________________________________________________

! + tab to create a html boiler


________________________________________________________________________________

*-* syntax *-*
________________________________________________________________________________

const <variable> = require('<package name>') //this is how to import package, this is default import syntax for node.js, but the browser don't understand the require(), so we use 

import * as express from 'express' //import everything as express from express

HTTP Request
 Many verbs (methods)
 GET
 POST
 PUT
 PATCH
 DELETE
 HEAD
 OPTIONS
 ...

app.get('/', (req, res)) => {})
=> handling HTTP get request, get is one of the verb, it can be use to access a resource
=> req -> request object
=> res -> respond object

app.listen(<port number>)
=> create an HTTP server, HTTP default port is 80, we usually can't use port <1000
=> the browser is accessing the HTTP server on our computer
________________________________________________________________________________

*-* packages *-*
________________________________________________________________________________

express -> to connect the back end to the front end
fs -> a built in package to handle file system
